uld service ideals, whether intellectual, political, religious, and social, even as they could simultaneously articulate fears; he argues that their material presence energizes works of art in paradoxical, even contradictory ways. In this way, Romanesque monsters resist containment within modern interpretive categories and offer testimony to the density and nuance of the medieval imagination. KIRK AMBROSE is Associate Professor & Chair, Department of Art and Art History, University of Colorado Boulder.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChristian art and symbolismyMedieval, 500-1500zEurope. 0aDecoration and ornament, ArchitecturalxThemes, motiveszEurope. 0aDecoration and ornament, RomanesquexThemes, motives. 0aMonsters in art. 0aSculpture, EuropeanxThemes, motivesy12th century. 0aSculpture, RomanesquexThemes, motives. 4aArt & Architecture. 7aART / Sculpture & Installation.2bisacsh  a12th century art.  aDark Age.  aFear in art.  aMedieval France.  aMedieval Manuscript.  aMedieval Portugal.  aMedieval monsters.  aMonsters in art.  aRomanesque monster.  aRomanesque sculpture.  aTwelfth-century.  agreen man.  agrotesques.  amedieval art.  amedieval sculture.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782045496?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782045496423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782045496/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles